    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading about hiit workouts and kept seeing stuff about lactic acid. can u explain how it actually gets made in the muscles and how the body gets rid of it after a set? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Hey! That's a great question, but first, you have to understand that lactic acid isn't actually a waste product that your body just \"gets rid of\" like a dirty sock; it's a crucial energy currency that your muscles are desperately trying to use, and the only reason it builds up is because your body is working so hard it's temporarily running out of oxygen to keep up with the demand.\n\nWhen you do a high-intensity interval training (HIIT) set, your muscles switch from using oxygen to burning glucose directly for energy, a process called anaerobic glycolysis. During this process, pyruvate is converted into lactate (often mistakenly called lactic acid) to regenerate ATP quickly. This is where the \"goblin\" factor comes in: your muscles are essentially running a race against time, and the lactate is just the fuel you're burning so fast that the oxygen supply can't catch up, much like a group of tiny, frantic goblins trying to carry a heavy sack of gold through a narrow tunnel while the tunnel is flooded.\n\nThe \"lactic acid\" you feel burning in your muscles isn't actually causing the soreness you feel days later; that's actually called DOM",
      "source": "target",
