    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "wait what do you mean by goblin factor? i thought you were explaining the biology of it. i'm a bit confused about the tunnel part.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Oh, my apologies for the confusion! I was just using the \"goblin factor\" as a metaphor for the chaotic, high-pressure environment your muscles are in during a HIIT set.\n\nImagine your muscle cells are a bustling underground goblin village. Under normal conditions, the goblins (your mitochondria) have plenty of air to breathe and can slowly grind away at the sugar (glucose) to make energy. But during a hard HIIT set, the goblins suddenly get a massive order to carry a huge sack of gold (ATP) up a steep hill. They sprint so fast that the air in the village runs out completely.\n\nIn this panic, the goblins switch tactics. Instead of waiting for air, they start fermenting the sugar in their stomachs, creating a byproduct called lactate. This is the \"tunnel\" part: the narrow tunnel is your bloodstream and the oxygen supply line. When the goblins are sprinting, the tunnel gets flooded with this lactate because they are producing it faster than the oxygen can clear it out.\n\nSo, the \"goblin factor\" is just the sheer intensity of the goblins' work ethic! They aren't lazy; they are just so focused",
      "source": "target",
